WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.600
Hi, everyone. I'm Catherine. I'm really excited to talk to you today about WeAreRLadies, which

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:19.879
is the ROKR for RLadies Global. What is a ROKR, you ask? Good question. A ROKR is a

00:00:19.879 --> 00:00:24.040
rotating curation account, which means that there's a rotating spokesperson for a given

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:28.680
social media account. And this is pretty intuitive for an organization like RLadies, because

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:33.680
we have 180 plus chapters worldwide, and there are so many awesome people doing such

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:39.919
amazing things. So every week, we have a different person curate or tweet from WeAreRLadies.

00:00:39.919 --> 00:00:44.439
They discuss their experiences, they discuss how they use R, and maybe some tips and tricks

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:52.000
along the way. Since this account started in August 2018, we've gained 15,000 plus followers.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.080
We've had 56 awesome curators across 19 different countries. And hopefully, there's more to

00:00:57.080 --> 00:01:02.439
come in 2020. This picture on the left is actually our very first tweet from our first

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:07.959
curator ever, which was Mara Averick. So if we look at the most frequently used words

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:12.180
from tweets in this account, you'll see that it looks very similar to what you might see

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:19.279
on the rstats hashtag, things like data, package, code. However, for every technical topic that

00:01:19.279 --> 00:01:23.720
we speak about, curators are really generous about talking about their experiences. They're

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:27.720
talking about what they love, their community, their learning journeys. And I think this

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:31.959
is really what makes this account special. And for me, at least, it's very similar to

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:40.120
what I might experience at my local RLadies chapter. Here is the most liked tweet of our

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:46.040
account thus far. And I think it's a little bit of both. It's explaining the package praise,

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:50.919
which got also a shout out this morning at Jenny Bryan's keynote. And it's just a fun

00:01:50.919 --> 00:01:57.559
package that people are really excited to learn about. However, not everything is fun,

00:01:57.559 --> 00:02:02.000
right? Our experiences are not only the fun stuff, but also the things that might be frustrating

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.300
about R. And we're all learning together, and no one seems to be an expert. So even

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:11.279
our curators have questions. One tweet that I really liked was from Sina, and she talked

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:17.880
about her frustration installing RCPP parallel. And basically every reply to this tweet was,

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:25.240
I'm so glad I'm not alone. So if we look at a really quick sentiment analysis of all

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:28.720
of the tweets on this account, we have the most negatively charged words on the left

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:32.399
and the most positively charged words on the right. We're a pretty positive group, I would

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:38.199
say. There are things that are negative about the tweets in our account, primarily driven

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:45.520
by, like, evil plots. Things like tricks and regression. Really, really negative. Conversely,

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:50.960
things that are positive is mainly because we love talking about things that are shiny.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:56.559
So it's really interesting what comes up when we do a sentiment analysis on this. But some

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:00.639
of this jargon aside, we're still talking about issues, get related or not, mistakes

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:05.479
and difficulties. And in a Twitter world where everyone seems like a superstar, this has

00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:11.399
been really comforting to me and made the Twitter community a little bit more accessible.

00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:16.279
In the 2700 tweets that are currently in this dataset, which doesn't even include

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:22.179
anyone this year, we've had about 400 plus questions and counting. Maybe there's a little

00:03:22.179 --> 00:03:26.679
bit more. This was a quick regular expression looking at all of the tweets that contained

00:03:26.679 --> 00:03:31.839
question marks. And basically we're seeing that everyone's asking questions, whether

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:37.240
they're a student or a senior data scientist. And these questions aren't only just about

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:41.119
our confusions. They're also just engaging conversation, which I think is really, really

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:44.880
awesome. One tweet that I really love from my friend

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:50.339
Kaylin, she asked people what they love about data science and or statistics. And she also

00:03:50.339 --> 00:03:54.160
just gave her response to this question as well. And the replies from this tweet were

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:58.520
just really, really awesome and really, really encouraging for someone who might be new to

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:03.440
the field. So I just want to end with maybe a shameless

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:08.880
plug. If you aren't following We Are Our Ladies, in my unbiased opinion, I think it's worth

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:15.000
following. And if you are interested, please just consider curating for We Are Our Ladies.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.040
It doesn't matter whether you're a beginner or whether you've been through the ringer

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:25.119
with R, we're all learning together and everyone's perspective is valuable. And this is something

00:04:25.119 --> 00:04:29.640
that I really have found to ring true from having to read every single tweet on this

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:35.040
account. So I just also want to close quickly with some acknowledgements. There's a lot

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:40.239
of great people who make this Roker happen. Particularly a huge thank you to the curators

00:04:40.239 --> 00:04:43.519
that make it worth following week after week. Thank you so much.

